<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 18  2:27:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Tom,<br>
First of all, anything you want to say to me can be said here.  It is obvious we don't agree, so what is the point in me giving my e-mail, so we can disagree more?  We can talk this out on this dialog.  Why do you want my e-mail?  For what reason?  <br><br>
  I can provide the testimony of a large number of vets who did NOT commit acts of violence (I'm talking murder and assault) against civilians, nor did they see them widespread!!!  Try and call them a liar!!! I never said acts of cruelty and violence were not commited against Vietnamese civilians, I said they were NOT widespread. My father was in Vietnam, and so were many of his friends (in a variety of units, locations, and time periods), and I swear by everything that is holy, that I believe them when they say the DID NOT commit acts of violence against civilians or witness them as a every day happening.  So are my father and many other vets I know Liars?  I have the right to speak, as a citizen, as a son of a Vietnam vet, as a person who has seen the pain of war in many others.  &quot;What is the point of dialog in good faith when only dialog that tickles our ears is listened to?&quot;  The door swings both ways, I have the right to my view.<br><br>
  In regards to acts of violence that you seem to think are commonplace, war is one big act of violence.  Last time I checked Tom, the job of the army was to kill people and destroy things, not plant rose gardens and have folk rock festivals.  War is a series of acts of violence, sometimes innocent people get hurt.  How about Dresden, Caen, Monte Cassino, Korea, Etc? Name one war where a civilian didn't get killed?  Since our military is made up of society, it has the same elements of society-the best and worst.  Sure, some men were cruel toward civilians in Nam (that is true and I accept that 100%), but my point is that actions of these people are just that of that particular individual.  These people would be cruel here in the US.  I question the policy and command that didn't fall on these men and punish severly.  This is what everyone needs to look at.  Why the military command allowed anything to happen, without punishment.  I am talking about how COMMONPLACE ACTS OF VIOLENCE SUCH AS MURDER AND ASSUALT WERE.  I don't believe these were commonplace based on credible eyewitness testimony.  In regards to my not having been there, your right, I rely on the word of good men that were.  But are you much different?  You may have served in Vietnam, but were you with every unit, in every location for the total 10 years of war?  Or do you rely on the testimony and word of others?  How do you come to the conclusion, these acts were widespread and commonplace?  What you saw in your area of operations is true for your unit, time of service etc.  If you make any other assumptions, or listen to the word of others, aside from the truth of your own eyes, that is hearsay too!  As you were so quick to accuse me!  Were you everywhere in Vietnam?  I don't doubt your word or experiences Tom, they are valid, but Vietnam has millions of experiences.  Therefore, if you say that these cruel acts and serious crimes (murder) and treatments were true everywhere and everytime during the war, then my statement that they were not stands as a valid argument too.  By the way I do have the right to speak!!! as a American, the son of a decorated Nam vet, and as a human being that has seen the pain in vets from the war and the readjustment coming home.<br>
In regards to Vets being afraid to come foward and say they saw these things, you said they are dismissed as being  liars or wannabe's.  Why do think that is so Tom?  Are all vets afraid that a couple of guys will tell the truth?  Or is it that many vets through their own experiences know them to be false?  Believe me there are enough forums for the vet to come foward.  How about Vietnam Veterans against the War?  There is a audience that will listen and they organized into a group?  I don't see 2.5 million vets running foward to confess, even when the political atmosphere was conducive to it and the general attitude was anti-war most did not.<br><br>
To All, Cook, Tom etc.<br>
The original part of this diagreement is over shots at people near perimeters.  If it was as target practice against civilians-that is sick, wrong, etc and command should have punished severly.  But sometimes civilians provided data for attacks.  My father remembers a guy that was pacing out areas in their basecamp, who was later found to be VC.  He had come in with the civilian employees for the 1st Cav at Bien Hoa.  So I can see the security issue of warning people away, as long as it was not done in a reckless, dangerous manner.<br><br>
Tom, how about we agree to disagree?  Both views have validity, yours from your tour, and mine from my father and the vets I know. That is a midpoint and a start.  Sorry to come off strong, but you did also.  Fighting divided America then, lets do what the title of the website says &quot;Dialog&quot;.  Keep it civil and open. 
